]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Conceptual Design & Modelling – A thermal incubator model is built from the physical laws using the energy equation Q = cmΔT and four simplifying assumptions (A–D). Two dynamic models are derived: Model A (all assumptions) and Model B (excluding Assumption 4 to capture heat‑bed inertia). Physical Twin Deployment – Hardware (styrofoam enclosure, heatbed, fan, two inside‑box temperature sensors, one outside sensor) is assembled on a Raspberry Pi and controlled by a bang‑bang controller parameterised by LL, UL, H and C. Digital Twin Integration – Model B is wrapped in a calibration routine that updates model parameters using a non‑linear least‑squares solver. Data from the PT are streamed through RabbitMQ by the low‑level driver and reused by the DT to keep the simulation synchronised. Runtime Monitoring & Iterative Refinement – During operation the DT continually (a) runs calibration on demand, (b) feeds observed temperatures into the model, and (c) checks safety/optimality metrics; anomalies are flagged using a Kalman filter estimating the unmeasured heatbed temperature. Governance & Evolution – All code, models and calibration scripts are stored in an open‑source GitHub repository (https://github.com/INTO‑CPS‑Association/example‑incubator) and versioned, allowing the Digital Twin to evolve with changing plant dynamics while preserving a clear audit trail of model updates."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The model fidelity is governed by four key assumptions: (1) the temperature inside the box is spatially uniform thanks to active fan circulation (Assumption 1); (2) the box walls do not accumulate significant heat that would affect the air temperature (Assumption 2); (3) the specific heat capacity of the air is treated as constant across the operating range (Assumption 3); and (4) the majority of electrical power is assumed to be converted to heat energy, thus the heatbed’s own heat absorption and fan heating are neglected (Assumption 4). Model validity is assessed through calibration experiments – sensor data are compared against the predictions of Model A and Model B, and a least‑squares optimiser adjusts the free parameters until residuals are minimized. Anomaly detection is integrated via a Kalman filter that estimates the unmeasured heatbed temperature; deviations from expected residuals trigger alerts. Validation also includes experiments verifying the uniform temperature distribution, verifying the negligible wall heat effect, and measuring sensor accuracy. All models and data undergo version control and are stored in the repository for reproducibility."
]

